newmandescr: Large circle with three rounded prongs emerging from top (forming a crown), the center one like a fleur-de-lis. Within the circle is another circle, about 5 mm from the first one. Within this is a rectangle, long side vertical, containing an image — it is possibly a lion standing on its hind legs, although it is very hard to make out. [Revision Feb 2016 adds]: Watermark is 91mm high x 72mm wide.  It is centered in the middle of four chains, and it completely fills the space.  The chains vary from 23 to 25mm apart.

newmandescr: Arms of the City of London, very clear.  From the bottom of the shield to the highest point of the prongs and flourishes at the top is 60mm. The widest points, furnished by two prongs at the top, give a width of c. 44mm.  The body of the shield proper, lower down, is 36mm.  The very clear chains are about 24mm apart.  I think this is the other half of Sheet 2.  The last words on Sheet 2v are “(as Compt Bernard assignes) for it is only after the ”     and Sheet 3r begins “conjunction of the female & male”.  So the pagination looks consecutive.  Also, the two sheets are each badly creased 50mm from the bottom from a previous fold.  The crease extends straight across the bottom of both sheets, and in fact both sheets are in dangerous of being fragmented by the crease.  Additionally, the “C T” and the dagger of the arms are both in the correct orientation when the sheets are placed next to one another in this fashion. newmandescr: Arms of the City of London, on “Fol. 1”, with the librarians’ “1” upside down.  This watermark is seen much more clearly on Sheet 6, on the page that the librarians have numbered “17”; also on Sheet 7, on “20”.  From top to bottom, the watermark measures about 100 mm.  Sideways it measures about 65 mm. from its widest points.  It is centered in a column made up of two chains, and it extends outward laterally on both sides until it almost touches two other chains leaving about 3 mm. on either side of its widest points between it and the respective chain.  The chains themselves are about 23 mm. apart.  [The watermark is very similar to the one pictured on a Newton MS. kept at Brandeis University, but whether the same one cannot tell without measurements.  See  ( http://brandeisspecialcollections.blogspot.com/2011_05_01_archive.html ).   The Brandeis shelfmark is not given there, but the MS., identified as “a gift of Philip D. Sang, is entitled “Certain Arguments collected out of ye Scriptures, out of ye Civill[sic] Law & ye Common exhibited to ye Queen Majesty by some or both houses against ye Queen of Scots”.”  ]    I see no countermarks on any of the sheets bearing this watermark.  Brandeis dates this “approximately 1683–1710.”

newmandescr: On “30” (rightside up) a Fleur-de-lis without crown or shield – perhaps this is a countermark.  It is about 56 mm. high and 40 mm. wide at its widest points.  A single chain runs down the middle of the fleur, forming its axis.  There are 3 to 5 mm. of space on either side of the widest points before a chain is reached.  So it is centered between three chains.  On the right half of the sheet, numbered “31” by librarians, there is a countermark “A I”.  The letters are about 13 mm. high and together measure about 22 mm. across at their widest point (their bases).  They are centered within three chains in such a way that they are very close to the central chain.  The right foot of the “A” actually touches the central chain.  There is a space of 12 mm. or so to the left of the “A” and 17 mm. or so to the right of the “I”.

newmandescr: A hunter’s horn within a shield, and the two letters “H G” hanging from the underside of the shield. A bigger countermark “M C” is found on the other end of the paper. Judging from the orientation of the watermark and countermark (on the original full sheet, the watermark would have been on the left and the countermark on the right), the MS. may originally have been folded and slit like CU add. 3973. The fold may later have separated. The chains are about 28 mm apart. The shield is located symmetrically such that a chain runs down its middle. The shield is about 69 mm from top to bottom, and about 50 mm wide at its widest point. The “H G” extends downward about 16 mm further. The widest parts of the shield are perhaps 4 mm on the left side from a chain and 2 mm. on the right, but this is hard to determine, since the chains are vague. The countermark is about 40 mm wide at the widest point (bottom) of the “M C”. The “M C” is about 8 mm high. The chains are too hard to make out accurately on this sheet, thanks to the heavy writing.

It could be an italic or cursive ""I"" but it is centered on the shield bottom above it, so the watermark cannot be identical to Shapiro, p. 193, fig. 3 (see Alan E. Shapiro, ""Beyond the Dating Game: Watermark Clusters and the Composition of Newton's Opticks,"" in P. M. Harman and Alan E. Shapiro, The Investigation of Difficult Things (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1992), pp. 181-227) . The crown and shield are quite similar to Shapiro's. But another detail is different — the horn is hanging from a string represented by a single line, not a strap.

newmandescr: An unusual watermark. It looks rather like a teapot with a fleur-de-lis surmounting it. The whole watermark is 134 mm high and 64 mm wide. It is centered within three columns formed by four chains. The chains are about 23 mm apart. The left hand broadest point is 2 mm from its chain and the right hand is 4 mm from its chain.

newmandescr: This sheet has no visible watermark.  But it is probably made of the same type of paper as Sheet 2. I say this because the paper has an odd peculiarity – the chains are irregularly spaced. The normal spacing in Sheet 1 is 23mm apart, but the lowest horizontal band is made of two chains that are only 18 or 19mm apart.  A similar thing happens on Sheet 2: the normal spacing is about 24mm apart, but the first complete band from the top is only 17mm across.  The evidence for the two sheets coming from the same piece of paper is not conclusive since there is no obvious matching of edges.
